name: r-r.matlab
raw_meta_yaml:
{% set version = '3.6.2' %}
{% set posix = 'm2-' if win else '' %}
{% set native = 'm2w64-' if win else '' %}

package:
  name: r-r.matlab
  version: {{ version|replace("-", "_") }}

source:
  url:
    - {{ cran_mirror }}/src/contrib/R.matlab_{{ version }}.tar.gz
    - {{ cran_mirror }}/src/contrib/Archive/R.matlab/R.matlab_{{ version }}.tar.gz
  sha256: 1ba338f470a24b7f6ef68cadbd04eb468ead4a689f263d2642408ad591b786bb

build:
  merge_build_host: True  # [win]
  number: 1003
  noarch: generic
  rpaths:
    - lib/R/lib/
    - lib/

requirements:
  build:
    - {{ posix }}zip               # [win]
  host:
    - r-base
    - r-r.methodss3 >=1.7.1
    - r-r.oo >=1.21.0
    - r-r.utils >=2.5.0
  run:
    - r-base
    - r-r.methodss3 >=1.7.1
    - r-r.oo >=1.21.0
    - r-r.utils >=2.5.0

test:
  commands:
    - $R -e "library('R.matlab')"           # [not win]
    - "\"%R%\" -e \"library('R.matlab')\""  # [win]

about:
  home: https://github.com/HenrikBengtsson/R.matlab
  license: LGPL-2.1-only
  summary: Methods readMat() and writeMat() for reading and writing MAT files.  For user with
    MATLAB v6 or newer installed (either locally or on a remote host), the package also
    provides methods for controlling MATLAB (trademark) via R and sending and retrieving
    data between R and MATLAB.
  license_family: LGPL
  license_file:
    - '{{ environ["PREFIX"] }}/lib/R/share/licenses/LGPL-2.1'

extra:
  recipe-maintainers:
    - conda-forge/r

# Package: R.matlab
# Version: 3.6.2
# Depends: R (>= 2.14.0)
# Imports: methods, utils, R.methodsS3 (>= 1.7.1), R.oo (>= 1.21.0), R.utils (>= 2.5.0)
# Suggests: Matrix, SparseM
# Date: 2018-09-26
# Title: Read and Write MAT Files and Call MATLAB from Within R
# Authors@R: c( person("Henrik", "Bengtsson", role=c("aut", "cre", "cph"), email="henrikb@braju.com"), person("Andy", "Jacobson", role="ctb", comment="Internal MAT v4 reader"), person("Jason", "Riedy", role="ctb", email="ejr@cs.berkeley.edu", comment="Support for reading compressed files, sparse matrices and UTF-encoded strings."))
